                        <p><b>Current mainstream media is designed to profit off your attention and time.</b></p>

<p><a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/24/opinion/sunday/surveillance-capitalism.html">Shoshana Zuboff</a> (2020), a professor emerita at the Harvard Business School likens the grasp and influence of social media on our psyche as a means of remote control.  She argues that current surveillance capitalist models of social media “undermines human agency, [usurps] privacy, [diminishes] autonomy and [deprives] individuals of the right to combat.</p>

<b><p>Design choices created to manipulate users are known as deceptive patterns</b> (<a href="https://www.deceptive.design/">Deceptive Patterns</a>, 2023).</p>

<p>Some deceptive patterns that social media employs to keep you on the hamster wheel include infinite scrolling, display of advert-isements in the same style as other content, and unclear privacy policies that are too hard to read.</p>
                    </div>
